      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Since you mentioned residential scaffolding, I have good news: OSHA regulations do not technically apply to structures under 12 feet, meaning there is no federal mandate for rigid platforms on residential jobs like \"Questioned by Regulator\" implies. I will focus on the next best thing, which is industry best practice and the \"red flag\" signs you used, specifically checking if the ground beneath is rigging up to a level where it might shift under load or if the foundation is a liquid bed that could cause collapse. To do this, you should visually inspect the foundation for significant cracks or water pooling, dig test holes where loads will be placed to see the depth of the soil, and ideally place heavy nhắmym明灯 under the load to see if the structure settles before allowing climbing. Remember to always use personal protective equipment (PPE) to compensate for any minor instability not caught by these checks.",
